Subject:    <a href="?t=95837891200006&r=1&w=2">How to have a domain and a cname with the same name</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837786400003&r=1&w=2">Roy Smith &lt;roy () alanine ! phri ! nyu ! edu&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198906">1989-06-30 10:35:38</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626949&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626949&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

	I run the phri.nyu.edu domain, in which there are a number of
hosts, one of which is phri.phri.nyu.edu which has the master mail aliases
data base (i.e. any mail addressed to person@phri.phri.nyu.edu will get
forwarded to the proper host).  It would be convenient to have people on
the outside simply send to person@phri.nyu.edu and have phri.nyu.edu be a
nickname for phri.phri.nyu.edu, but I can't seem to figure out any way to
do that.  If I do the obvious and put a CNAME record in:

phri.nyu.edu.	IN	CNAME	phri.phri.nyu.edu.

I get complaints about how phri.nyu.edu has both a CNAME and other
information, which is illegal (I'm running BIND, if that makes any
difference).  What is the right way to do what I want to do?

